{
  "$schema": "https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/schema",
  "$id": "https://github.com/armelhbobdad/bmad-module-skill-forge/src/shared/scripts/schemas/skill-brief.v1.json",
  "title": "skill-brief.yaml (v1)",
  "description": "Canonical schema for the skill-brief.yaml artifact written by skf-brief-skill step 5 and consumed by skf-create-skill, skf-update-skill, skf-audit-skill. Mirrors src/skf-brief-skill/assets/skill-brief-schema.md.",
  "type": "object",
  "required": ["name", "version", "source_repo", "language", "description", "forge_tier", "created", "created_by", "scope"],
  "properties": {
    "name": {
      "type": "string",
      "pattern": "^[a-z0-9]([a-z0-9-]*[a-z0-9])?$",
      "description": "Unique skill identifier (kebab-case)."
    },
    "version": {
      "type": "string",
      "pattern": "^v?\\d+\\.\\d+\\.\\d+([.\\-+][0-9A-Za-z][0-9A-Za-z.\\-+]*)?$",
      "description": "Resolved semver. target_version wins; else auto-detected; else 1.0.0."
    },
    "target_version": {
      "type": "string",
      "pattern": "^v?\\d+\\.\\d+\\.\\d+([.\\-+][0-9A-Za-z][0-9A-Za-z.\\-+]*)?$",
      "description": "User-specified target. When present, MUST equal version."
    },
    "target_ref": {
      "type": "string",
      "minLength": 1,
      "description": "Optional explicit git ref (tag or branch) used verbatim as source_ref, bypassing version-to-tag matching. Escape hatch for monorepo crate tags whose prefix differs from the skill name (e.g. tag livekit/v0.7.42 for skill livekit-rust). Remote sources only. Mutually exclusive with constituent_refs."
    },
    "constituent_refs": {
      "type": "object",
      "additionalProperties": { "type": "string", "minLength": 1 },
      "description": "Per-constituent git ref overrides for composite (multi-repo or multi-ref) sources. Keys must match entries in the analyze-source project_paths array. When absent, a single target_ref or auto-detected ref applies to all paths. Mutually exclusive with target_ref."
    },
    "source_type": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": ["source", "docs-only"]
    },
    "source_repo": {
      "type": "string",
      "minLength": 1,
      "description": "GitHub URL or local path. Required even for docs-only (set to doc site URL)."
    },
    "source_authority": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": ["official", "community", "internal"]
    },
    "doc_urls": {
      "type": "array",
      "items": {
        "type": "object",
        "required": ["url"],
        "properties": {
          "url": { "type": "string", "minLength": 1 },
          "label": { "type": "string" }
        }
      },
      "minItems": 1,
      "description": "Required when source_type is docs-only; allowed as supplemental for source."
    },
    "language": { "type": "string", "minLength": 1 },
    "description": { "type": "string", "minLength": 1 },
    "forge_tier": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": ["Quick", "Forge", "Forge+", "Deep"]
    },
    "created": {
      "type": "string",
      "pattern": "^\\d{4}-\\d{2}-\\d{2}$"
    },
    "created_by": { "type": "string", "minLength": 1 },
    "scripts_intent": { "type": "string", "minLength": 1 },
    "assets_intent": { "type": "string", "minLength": 1 },
    "scope": {
      "type": "object",
      "required": ["type", "include", "exclude", "notes"],
      "properties": {
        "type": {
          "type": "string",
          "enum": ["full-library", "specific-modules", "public-api", "component-library", "reference-app", "docs-only"]
        },
        "include": { "type": "array", "items": { "type": "string" } },
        "exclude": { "type": "array", "items": { "type": "string" } },
        "notes": { "type": "string" },
        "rationale": {
          "type": "object",
          "description": "Optional authoring-time scope-type decision record written once by skf-brief-skill step 03. Absent on legacy briefs.",
          "required": ["recommended", "chosen", "accepted_recommendation", "heuristic", "reason", "recorded"],
          "additionalProperties": false,
          "properties": {
            "recommended": {
              "type": "string",
              "enum": ["full-library", "specific-modules", "public-api", "component-library", "reference-app", "docs-only"]
            },
            "chosen": {
              "type": "string",
              "enum": ["full-library", "specific-modules", "public-api", "component-library", "reference-app", "docs-only"]
            },
            "accepted_recommendation": { "type": "boolean" },
            "heuristic": { "type": "string", "minLength": 1 },
            "reason": { "type": "string", "minLength": 1 },
            "recorded": { "type": "string", "pattern": "^\\d{4}-\\d{2}-\\d{2}$" }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}

{
  "_comment": "Canonical companion prose corpora for whole-language skills (issue #427). A language-reference repo (a compiler/interpreter such as rust-lang/rust) carries the language's CODE; its value as a skill comes from the language's PROSE — the guide/Book, the standard/library API docs, and idioms. README detection (skf-detect-docs.py) is the primary source; this registry guarantees the canonical corpora for well-known languages even when the repo's README does not link them. Keyed by lowercase language id (as emitted by skf-detect-language.py / step-auto-scope.md). URLs are version-agnostic, point at maintained latest-stable aliases, and were verified live. Consumed by skf-language-corpora.py, which emits the brief doc_urls contract {url, label}.",
  "rust": [
    { "url": "https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/", "label": "The Rust Programming Language (Book)" },
    { "url": "https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/", "label": "Rust Standard Library" },
    { "url": "https://doc.rust-lang.org/reference/", "label": "The Rust Reference" }
  ],
  "python": [
    { "url": "https://docs.python.org/3/tutorial/", "label": "The Python Tutorial" },
    { "url": "https://docs.python.org/3/library/", "label": "Python Standard Library" },
    { "url": "https://docs.python.org/3/reference/", "label": "Python Language Reference" },
    { "url": "https://docs.python.org/3/howto/", "label": "Python HOWTOs (idioms)" }
  ],
  "go": [
    { "url": "https://go.dev/tour/", "label": "A Tour of Go" },
    { "url": "https://go.dev/doc/effective_go", "label": "Effective Go" },
    { "url": "https://go.dev/ref/spec", "label": "The Go Language Specification" },
    { "url": "https://pkg.go.dev/std", "label": "Go Standard Library" }
  ],
  "typescript": [
    { "url": "https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/intro.html", "label": "TypeScript Handbook" },
    { "url": "https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/", "label": "TypeScript Documentation (Reference)" }
  ],
  "javascript": [
    { "url": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Guide", "label": "MDN JavaScript Guide" },
    { "url": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference", "label": "MDN JavaScript Reference" }
  ],
  "ruby": [
    { "url": "https://www.ruby-lang.org/en/documentation/quickstart/", "label": "Ruby in Twenty Minutes" },
    { "url": "https://docs.ruby-lang.org/en/master/", "label": "Ruby Core & Standard Library API" }
  ]
}

input.script:
export const meta = {
  name: 'design-427-followups',
  description: 'Design + adversarially red-team the four #427 follow-up issues (#430/#431/#432/#433) before implementation',
  phases: [
    { title: 'Design', detail: 'one design agent per issue, verifies its own lockstep surface' },
    { title: 'RedTeam', detail: 'adversarial verification of risky designs (regression, completeness)' },
  ],
}

const REPO = '/home/armel/Projects/OSS/bmad-module-skill-forge'

const DESIGN_SCHEMA = {
  type: 'object',
  additionalProperties: false,
  required: ['issue', 'approach_summary', 'files_to_change', 'new_or_changed_tests', 'risks', 'interactions', 'open_questions', 'verified_facts'],
  properties: {
    issue: { type: 'string' },
    approach_summary: { type: 'string', description: '3-6 sentence chosen approach' },
    files_to_change: {
      type: 'array',
      items: {
        type: 'object',
        additionalProperties: false,
        required: ['path', 'change', 'why'],
        properties: {
          path: { type: 'string' },
          change: { type: 'string', description: 'concrete edit, with line refs where known' },
          why: { type: 'string' },
        },
      },
    },
    new_or_changed_tests: { type: 'array', items: { type: 'string' } },
    risks: { type: 'array', items: { type: 'string' } },
    interactions: { type: 'string', description: 'how this issue depends on / is depended on by the other three' },
    open_questions: { type: 'array', items: { type: 'string' } },
    verified_facts: { type: 'array', items: { type: 'string' }, description: 'claims you confirmed by reading the actual files this run, with file:line' },
  },
}

const VERDICT_SCHEMA = {
  type: 'object',
  additionalProperties: false,
  required: ['lens', 'holds', 'severity', 'findings', 'must_fix'],
  properties: {
    lens: { type: 'string' },
    holds: { type: 'boolean', description: 'true if the design survives this lens' },
    severity: { type: 'string', enum: ['none', 'low', 'medium', 'high'] },
    findings: { type: 'array', items: { type: 'string' } },
    must_fix: { type: 'array', items: { type: 'string' }, description: 'concrete changes the design must adopt to survive' },
  },
}

const COMMON = `You are designing a change in the bmad-module-skill-forge repo at ${REPO}. This is a BMad module that "forges" Claude Code skills from source repos. The four issues all descend from PR #429 (issue #427), which added a whole-language "language-reference" shape. VERIFY every claim by READING the actual files (cite file:line). Do not invent. Output is consumed by an orchestrator, not a human — return only the structured object. Conventions that MATTER: cross-platform Python (Path.as_posix, utf-8 reads, O_BINARY writes); package.json test:python must enumerate any NEW test file; changes must be byte-identical for skills/briefs that do NOT match the targeted shape (no false drift); commits feature-focused, no internal refs.`

const ISSUES = [
  {
    key: '432',
    risk: 'high',
    title: 'Carry per-corpus provenance (source/detected_via) through doc_urls schema + brief writer',
    context: `Map and design the FULL doc_urls lockstep. Confirmed facts to verify and extend:
- Schema src/shared/scripts/schemas/skill-brief.v1.json lines 47-59: doc_urls items = {url (required), label}. items has NO "additionalProperties: false", so extra keys ALREADY pass schema validation today (additive change is non-breaking).
- Writer src/shared/scripts/skf-write-skill-brief.py: validate_context() lines ~234-242 only validates 'url'; assemble_brief() lines ~436-440 REBUILDS each entry as {"url":..., "label":...} — THIS IS THE DROP POINT that discards any extra field. flat_to_nested() passes doc_urls through unchanged (not a scope key).
- skf-detect-docs.py ALREADY emits detected_via in {homepageUrl, readme_link, pages_api, docs_folder} (lines 240, 284, 299, 316). content_type + content_hash too.
- skf-language-corpora.py emits ONLY {url,label} — registry corpora carry no provenance.
- Brief-side stamp/merge site: src/skf-brief-skill/references/step-auto-brief.md §3 (lines 86-101) converts detected docs to {url,label} (DROPS detected_via) then merges with upstream corpora-seeded entries (normalized-URL dedup, existing wins).
- Corpora seed site: src/skf-analyze-source/references/step-auto-scope.md §6b/§8 (lines 598-605) writes corpora as {url,label}.
- Consumer: src/skf-create-skill/references/step-doc-sources.md uses detected_via internally (readme_always etc.).
- Validators: skf-validate-brief-schema.py uses Draft202012Validator (additive-safe); skf-validate-brief-inputs.py treats doc_urls opaquely.
- Prose schema mirrors: src/skf-brief-skill/assets/skill-brief-schema.md, src/skf-analyze-source/assets/skill-brief-schema.md.
- Tests touching doc_urls: test/test-skf-write-skill-brief.py, test/test-skf-validate-brief-schema.py, test/test-skf-detect-docs.py, test/test-skf-step-doc-sources.py, test/test-skf-validate-brief-inputs.py.
DESIGN DECISION you must make and justify: field naming. Options: (a) single 'source' coarse enum {language-registry, readme-detection, homepage, pages-api, docs-folder}; (b) keep fine 'detected_via' (already exists in detect-docs) AND add coarse 'source' to distinguish registry-guaranteed vs opportunistic; (c) just extend 'detected_via' with a 'language-corpora' value. The issue wants to "distinguish registry-guaranteed corpora from opportunistically-detected docs." Recommend ONE and list EXACTLY which schema/writer/stamp/mirror/test edits it requires. Enumerate the COMPLETE lockstep surface — every reader, writer, validator, schema, prose mirror, and test — and confirm each is either changed or provably unaffected. This is foundational: #431 filters by it and #430 gates on it.`,
  },
  {
    key: '431',
    risk: 'medium',
    title: 'Suppress non-corpus README noise in language-reference doc_urls',
    context: `Confirmed facts:
- Brief-side merge site: src/skf-brief-skill/references/step-auto-brief.md §3 line 101 — dedup by normalized URL (lowercase host, strip trailing /index.html and /), existing/corpora-seeded entries win.
- skf-detect-docs.py _EXCLUSION_PATTERNS (lines 70-79) already drops CHANGELOG/CHANGES/HISTORY/MIGRATION/RELEASE/CONTRIBUTING/CODE_OF_CONDUCT/LICENSE/SECURITY. It does NOT drop /whatsnew/, /contribute (without ING), /wiki/, nor collapse non-primary-locale dupes (/ja/master/ vs /en/master/).
- Issue: for the language-reference shape, when a registry corpus exists for a doc HOST, drop README doc_urls on that SAME host whose path is a known non-corpus segment (/whatsnew/, /contribute, /wiki/), and collapse non-primary-locale duplicates. Keep scoped to whole-language references so ordinary skills are unaffected.
- This DEPENDS ON #432: needs the per-entry 'source' to know which entries are README-detected vs registry-seeded, and which host has a registry corpus.
- The vendored-grammar denylist (_GRAMMAR_COLLECTION_NAMES in skf-shape-detect.py) is "add only if a real false positive is observed" — investigate whether any real FP exists; default is DEFER if none observed (say so explicitly).
DESIGN: where does suppression live — brief-side step-auto-brief.md §3 (language-ref-scoped, has the merge + #432 source) or skf-detect-docs.py (shape-agnostic, wrong layer)? Define the non-corpus path segment set and the primary-locale rule precisely. Prove ordinary (non-language-ref) skills and legitimate corpora are never dropped. List tests (test/test-skf-detect-docs.py and/or a new brief-merge test — note package.json test:python must enumerate any new file).`,
  },
  {
    key: '430',
    risk: 'high',
    title: 'Rank prose above code in create-skill assembly for whole-language reference skills',
    context: `THE DEEPEST, HIGHEST-REGRESSION-RISK issue. Confirmed facts:
- There is NO explicit code-before-prose section ordering today. SKILL.md is built on a LIBRARY-EXPORT model: src/skf-create-skill/assets/compile-assembly-rules.md defines Tier1 (Overview/Quick Start/Common Workflows/Key API Summary/Key Types/Architecture) then Tier2 (Full API Reference). Doc/prose content is fetched as T3 and merged at the EXPORT level: src/skf-create-skill/references/sub/fetch-docs.md line 132 "T3 items NEVER override existing T1/T1-low/T2 items"; compile.md §1b "T1 AST signatures authoritative, T2/T3 may only ADD descriptions". So prose is structurally subordinated to compiler exports.
- compile-assembly-rules.md ALREADY HAS scoped assembly overrides per shape: "Component Library Assembly Overrides", "Reference-App Assembly Overrides", and within the latter a "Language / spec-reference sub-shape" clause (for scope.type reference-app DSLs like SurrealQL). These are GATED on scope.type and leave other shapes untouched — this is the PATTERN TO MIRROR.
- BUT the whole-language language-reference shape maps to scope.type = full-library (src/skf-analyze-source/references/step-shape-detect.md line 56 + step-auto-scope.md §4), NOT a distinct enum. So scope.type alone CANNOT gate it (every ordinary library is also full-library). The reference_skf_scope_type_enum_surface memory says adding a scope.type value is a ~25-file lockstep — AVOID.
- The ONLY whole-language signal that survives into the brief today is scope.notes containing the substring "LANGUAGE-REFERENCE CAVEAT" (written by step-auto-scope.md line 449). That caveat currently SAYS "Assembly ranks code (T1) above docs (T3) — review the forged skill if compiler-internal signatures dominate" — #430 must UPDATE this text.
- create-skill loads the brief in src/skf-create-skill/references/load-brief.md; assembly is compile.md §2 reading compile-assembly-rules.md. The brief's doc_urls + scope.notes are available there.
- INTERACTION WITH #432: if #432 stamps registry corpora with source:language-registry, then create-skill gets a RELIABLE machine gate ("doc_urls has an entry with source=language-registry") instead of grepping scope.notes prose. STRONGLY prefer designing #430 to consume the #432 signal.
RECOMMENDED APPROACH to evaluate: a NEW gated "Whole-Language Reference Assembly Overrides" section in compile-assembly-rules.md (mirroring the reference-app override), entered ONLY when the gate fires, that foregrounds a prose/language-guide section sourced from the corpora and demotes the compiler-export API summary. Because it is a NEW branch entered only on the gate, non-gated skills run the IDENTICAL existing code path (zero regression). 
YOU MUST: (1) define the exact gate signal and where it's derived; (2) specify the override section contents + where prose lands vs code; (3) PROVE no regression for non-whole-language skills (enumerate gate conditions + negative controls: ordinary library, parser-library like pest where §6b is skipped, component-library, reference-app); (4) update the step-auto-scope.md line 449 caveat; (5) define how to validate empirically (a real rust/TypeScript/cpython forge is heavy — propose a realistic proxy: deterministic gate-derivation test + a minimal forge/assembly check); (6) note that markdown/LLM-driven assembly is hard to unit-test — what CAN be deterministically tested.`,
  },
  {
    key: '433',
    risk: 'low',
    title: 'Extend shape detection to Maven (pom.xml), Gradle (build.gradle*), Swift (Package.swift)',
    context: `INDEPENDENT of the doc_urls chain. Confirmed facts:
- skf-scan-manifests.py MANIFEST_ECOSYSTEMS (lines ~104-119) ALREADY maps pom.xml->maven, build.gradle->gradle, build.gradle.kts->gradle, Package.swift->swift, and already has parsers parse_pom_xml/parse_gradle/parse_package_swift. So the scanner discovers them; shape-detect does NOT classify them.
- skf-shape-detect.py: _PARSERS dict (lines ~660-665) has only package.json/pyproject.toml/Cargo.toml/go.mod. go.mod was added via _parse_go_mod (lines ~612-657) returning {ecosystem, name, deps, runtime_deps, has_bin, has_library_structure, export_count}; path_to_manifest_name() (lines ~922-924) maps ecosystem->manifest-name. The detect() ladder classifies has_library_structure repos as library-API (rung 4, lines ~904-915).
- step-shape-detect.md line 25 lists "Supported manifests: package.json, pyproject.toml, Cargo.toml, go.mod" — must add the three.
- step-auto-scope.md §2: sparse-checkout glob (lines ~269-273) and the supported-manifest filter (line ~281) currently list go.mod — mirror for the three new manifests; also the include/exclude pattern generation (§5) per source-dir convention (Maven/Gradle src/main/{java,kotlin}, Swift Sources/).
- skf-detect-language.py _MANIFEST_RULES (lines ~88-98): has pom.xml->java, build.gradle.kts->kotlin; VERIFY whether build.gradle (Groovy) and Package.swift->swift are present — Package.swift is likely MISSING (must add). Language ids must be consistent across scan-manifests, shape-detect, detect-language.
- Tests: test/test-skf-shape-detect.py has a TestGoMod class (lines ~666-720) with a write_go_mod helper — mirror it. Check test/test-skf-scan-manifests.py.
SCOPE GUARD: these ecosystems produce ordinary library-API/full-library skills, NOT whole-language references — so DO NOT add language-corpora.json entries (corpora are only for grammar/tree whole-language refs). Keep this minimal: parsers + _PARSERS registration + path_to_manifest_name + detect-language Package.swift rule + step-shape-detect.md doc + step-auto-scope.md filter/glob/patterns + tests. Confirm the exact has_bin / source-dir conventions per ecosystem (Maven/Gradle have plugins/apps; Swift has executable targets). Each ecosystem is an independent incremental addition.`,
  },
]

phase('Design')
const results = await pipeline(
  ISSUES,
  // Stage 1: design, verifying the real files
  (iss) => agent(
    `${COMMON}\n\nISSUE #${iss.key}: ${iss.title}\n\n${iss.context}\n\nProduce the complete design for ONLY issue #${iss.key}. Read the cited files to verify every fact before relying on it.`,
    { label: `design:#${iss.key}`, phase: 'Design', schema: DESIGN_SCHEMA }
  ).then((d) => ({ iss, design: d })),

  // Stage 2: red-team. High-risk → 3 distinct lenses; med/low → 1 completeness critic.
  (r) => {
    if (!r || !r.design) return null
    const { iss, design } = r
    const designJson = JSON.stringify(design)
    let lenses
    if (iss.key === '430') {
      lenses = [
        `REGRESSION lens: The claim is that the gated whole-language assembly override leaves EVERY non-whole-language skill byte-identical. Try hard to REFUTE it. Read src/skf-create-skill/assets/compile-assembly-rules.md and compile.md. Does the proposed gate fire ONLY for whole-language refs? Enumerate negative controls (ordinary full-library library, parser-library pest where §6b is skipped so no registry corpora, component-library, reference-app, docs-only). Could any of them accidentally trip the gate? Could the override edit change the non-gated code path? Default to holds=false if the regression argument has ANY hole.`,
        `SIGNAL-RELIABILITY lens: Is the proposed gate signal actually present and reliable at assembly time (compile.md §2)? Trace it from the brief. If it depends on #432's source:language-registry field, is that guaranteed to be set for whole-language refs and absent otherwise? What about a whole-language ref whose corpora came ONLY from README detection (registry miss, exit 1 in skf-language-corpora.py)? What about scope.notes-substring gating fragility? Read step-auto-scope.md §6b and step-auto-brief.md §3. Refute reliability if there is a realistic case where the gate misfires or misses.`,
        `VALUE lens: Even if gated correctly, does the override actually deliver "prose ranked above code"? Read fetch-docs.md (T3 merge) and compile-assembly-rules.md. If prose is still fetched as T3 export-level items subordinated to T1, does merely adding a leading prose section achieve the goal, or does the T3-never-overrides-T1 rule still bury the language guide? Identify whether deeper changes are needed and whether the empirical-validation proxy proposed is sufficient to PROVE the behavior.`,
      ]
    } else if (iss.key === '432') {
      lenses = [
        `COMPLETENESS lens: The design claims to enumerate the FULL doc_urls lockstep. Try to find ONE reader, writer, validator, schema, prose mirror, envelope, or test that touches doc_urls and is NEITHER changed NOR provably unaffected. Grep the repo yourself (rg "doc_urls" across src/ test/). Check skf-emit-brief-result-envelope.py + its schema, scope-templates.md, confirm-brief.md, write-brief.md, re-extract.md (update-skill), and the brief-result-envelope schema. Default holds=false if any surface is unaccounted for.`,
        `BACKWARD-COMPAT lens: Will the new field cause false drift or break round-tripping? A ratify/re-write of an OLD brief (no provenance field) must stay byte-identical. A brief WITH the field must round-trip without loss. Does assemble_brief()'s conditional-emit logic (lines 436-440) handle absent provenance correctly? Does emitting the field unconditionally inject it into briefs that omitted it (the same anti-pattern the code calls out for source_authority at lines 448-454)? Refute if there is a drift or round-trip hole.`,
      ]
    } else {
      lenses = [
        `COMPLETENESS + CONSISTENCY lens: Find any surface the design missed. For #${iss.key}, verify by reading the cited files. ${iss.key === '433' ? 'Check that language ids are consistent across skf-scan-manifests.py, skf-shape-detect.py, skf-detect-language.py for java/kotlin/groovy/swift; confirm build.gradle (Groovy, no .kts) is handled; confirm package.json test:python lists any new test file; confirm NO language-corpora.json entry is added (scope guard).' : 'Confirm the suppression is language-reference-scoped and cannot drop legitimate corpora or any non-language-ref skill doc; confirm it depends correctly on #432 source; confirm the vendored-grammar denylist is correctly deferred unless a real FP exists.'} Default holds=false if anything is unaccounted for.`,
      ]
    }
    return parallel(lenses.map((lensPrompt, i) => () =>
      agent(
        `${COMMON}\n\nYou are adversarially RED-TEAMING a proposed design for issue #${iss.key}: ${iss.title}.\n\nPROPOSED DESIGN (JSON):\n${designJson}\n\n${lensPrompt}\n\nBe skeptical and concrete. Set lens to a short name. holds=true only if the design genuinely survives this lens.`,
        { label: `redteam:#${iss.key}:${i + 1}`, phase: 'RedTeam', schema: VERDICT_SCHEMA }
      )
    )).then((verdicts) => ({ issue: iss.key, title: iss.title, risk: iss.risk, design, verdicts: verdicts.filter(Boolean) }))
  }
)

return results.filter(Boolean)

